page.title: Speed
page.text: Why is Photoshop so much faster for image processing than our |cs1media| programs?
Because computers do not speak Python\ldots
A computer directly understands only one kind of language---its \dred{machine language}. This language is different for different CPUs.

Each number means some instruction: \begin{itemize} \item Load value from memory to CPU register \item Add two register values \item Store register value to memory \item Compare two numbers \item Jump to a new memory address \end{itemize}

page.title: Interpreters \& Compilers
page.text: Machine language instructions are very fast: A 2 GHz processor executes 2,000,000,000 instructions per second!
But machine instructions are very primitive, and nobody programs in machine language anymore.
Python uses an \dred{interpreter}: An interpreter is a program that reads your Python code and executes its instructions one after another.
Other interpreted languages are Scheme, \textsc{Matlab}, or Flash.
Languages such as C, C++, Java, or \textsc{Fortran} are \dred{compiled}. The input program (source code) is converted to a numeric format that contains machine instructions.

page.title: Interpreters \& Compilers
page.text: Using an interpreter is like making a dish using a cooking book in a foreign language that you cannot read well. You need to look up many words, and you execute the recipe slowly.
When we have to cook the same dish many times, it is more efficient to first translate the recipe and to write it down in your mother tongue. This is what a compiler does.
It takes time and effort to do the translation and to write it down. It is not worth doing that if we only cook the dish once. But now we can cook the dish many times quickly.

page.title: Why interpreters?
page.text: The Python shell interactively executes our instructions, so we can experiment with objects of different types and test their behavior.
We can also interactively explore data, or perform mathematical analysis (try symbolic differentiation in C++!).
An interpreter makes it easier to debug a program, because changing the program is fast. We can also look at the objects created in the program.
Memory-management is done automatically by the interpreter.

page.title: Smarter algorithms
page.text: Why is Photoshop faster than our 'posterize' function?
Photoshop is written in C++ and compiled to machine language.
Photoshop uses smarter algorithms.
A smart algorithm in an interpreted language can easily beat a simple algorithm in a compiled language.

page.title: Example: Sorting
page.text: If the list |a| has $n$ elements, then the |if| statement is executed $(n-1)^2$ times.
On a 2.8 GHz desktop, sorting 10000 numbers takes 20~seconds.

page.title: Merge Sort: a smarter algorithm
page.text: We partition the list into small pieces of one element.
Then we \dred{merge} pieces together in pairs, until the whole list is sorted.
Merging two sorted lists |a| and |b| is easy, as in each step we only need to select an element from either |a| or |b|.
We can show that this algorithm compares two list elements only $n \log_2 n$ times.
Sorting 10000 numbers on the same desktop computer takes 0.1~seconds. One million numbers can be sorted in 11~seconds.

page.title: Algorithm analysis
page.text: Designing \dred{efficient} algorithms for a problem is a fundamental branch of computer science.
Here, ``efficient'' means that we can prove that the number of operations made by the algorithm is bounded by some function of the problem size~$n$.
An algorithm is \dred{optimal} if we can prove that no algorithm can possibly solve the problem with a smaller number of operations (asymptotically).
We can prove that it is impossible to sort $n$ numbers with less than $n \log_2 n$ comparisons, and therefore Merge Sort is optimal.

page.title: Recursion
page.text: ``Recursion'' means to define something in terms of itself.
A folder is a collection of files and folders.
Words in dictionaries are defined in terms of other words.

page.title: A recursive function
page.text: Factorial \[ n! = \left\{ \begin{array}{l l} 1 & \quad \text{if $n=0$}\\ (n-1)! \times n & \quad \text{if $n>0$}\\ \end{array} \right. \]

page.text: \dred{Travelling Salesman}: Given $n$ points in the plane, find the shortest tour that visits all the points.
Best known algorithm needs roughly $2^n$ operations.
Nobody can prove that $n^2$ operations is impossible.
Million-dollar question: \[ P = NP \;\; \textrm{?} \]
There are problems for which we can prove that no algorithm exists.
